    "body": "I think the problem is not state availability, the problem is that erigon does not respect filter requests semantics. For example, let's say we have request:\r\n```\r\n{\r\n  \"method\": \"eth_newFilter\",\r\n  \"params\": [{\r\n    \"address\":[\"0xdAC17F958D2ee523a2206206994597C13D831ec7\"],\r\n    \"fromBlock\": \"0x11483b9\",\r\n    \"toBlock\": \"0x11483ba\"\r\n  }],\r\n  \"id\": \"100\",\r\n  \"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\"\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nSo, basically we create a useless filter, because it should update.\r\n\r\nExpected behaviour that eth_getFilterLogs would return all logs from block 0x11483b9 to 0x11483ba, while eth_getFilterChanges should return empty array indefinitely. This behaviour can be observed with Nethermind and SaaS like infura.\r\n\r\nHowever, erigon (v2.48.1) just ignores from/to block parameters. It just returns all logs from subsequent blocks (after filter was created), moreover the semantics of eth_getFilterLogs is the same as eth_getFilterChanges, so those methods for erigon are identical. ",
